      <hedline>
        <hl1>Plane or Train? The Joys and the Burdens</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Polson Kanneth letter comments on September 21 editorial urging Congress to enhance Amtrak's ability to ease burden on nation's congested skies and highways by passing High Speed Rail Investment Act before it adjourns; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Speedier Trains'' (editorial, Sept. 21):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Speedier Trains'' (editorial, Sept. 21):</p>
        <p>With airplanes across the country overcrowded, we have to give more attention to Amtrak. Over the last century, the use of trains has diminished with the advent of air travel and automobiles. But now that it is harder to book a flight, and getting to the airport requires a vacation in itself, we must focus on enhancing Amtrak's operations. Congress must support Amtrak fully because its constituents need Amtrak's services.</p>
        <p>Airlines and Amtrak need to work together in synchronizing their schedules to allow passengers to make connections from the airport to the train station, and vice versa.</p>
        <p>My experiences riding Amtrak have been much more soothing than flying.</p>
        <p>POLSON KANNETH  Spring Valley, N.Y., Sept. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
